>If you wish to carry out works affecting a public sewer you must consult the sewer authority (or in Scotland, <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.scottishwater.co.uk/\" title=\"Scottish Water\">Scottish Water</a>) before giving notice.</p>\n\n<p>Where your apparatus is to be affected by other major works you must consult with the local authority and take any necessary measures regarding the apparatus in order to secure efficient implementation of the works in question.</p>\n\n<p>If your works are likely to affect another person&rsquo;s apparatus you must comply with any reasonable requirement to allow them to protect or access their apparatus.</p>\n\n<p>You must reinstate the street as soon as practicable after the completion of your street works, and you must give notice to the local authority within ten working days of the reinstatement. In Scotland, this notice must be given by the working day following the completion.</p>\n\n<p>If the reinstatement is interim, you must complete permanent reinstatement as soon as possible, and within six months from the completion of the interim reinstatement.</p>\n\n<p>Permanent reinstatement must include reinstatement of features designed to assist people with a disability, and must comply with any requirements on materials to be used, standards of workmanship and performance standards.</p>\n\n<h2>Fines and penalties</h2>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>If you fail to comply with any of the conditions, you may be fined up to £5,000.</p>\n</div>\n"},"tags":[{"title":"Licences and licence applications","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/business%2Flicences.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Applying for licences from your council for events and businesses","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=business%2Flicences","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/business/licences"},"parent":{"title":"Businesses and self-employed","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/business.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Information about starting up and running a business in the UK, including help if you're self employed or a sole trader.","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=business","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/business"},"parent":null}}],"related":[]},{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/temporary-events-notice.json","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/temporary-events-notice","title":"Temporary Events Notice (England and Wales)","format":"licence","updated_at":"2012-10-22T15:23:00+00:00","details":{"need_id":"B200","business_proposition":true,"description":"You need a Temporary Event Notice if you want to carry out a 'licensable activity' on unlicensed premises in England or Wales","language":"en","alternative_title":"Apply for a Temporary Event Notice (England and Wales)","will_continue_on":"","continuation_link":"","licence_identifier":"1071-5-1","licence_short_description":"A Temporary Event Notice is for carrying out a 'licensable activity' on unlicensed premises. ","licence_overview":"\n<div class=\"summary\">\n<p>Contact your council for a Temporary Event Notice (<abbr title=\"Temporary Event Notice\">TEN</abbr>) if you want to carry out a ‘licensable activity’ on unlicensed premises in England or Wales.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>The process of applying is formally known as ‘serving’ a Temporary Event Notice.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>Licensable activity includes:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>selling alcohol</li>\n  <li>serving alcohol to members of a private club</li>\n  <li>providing entertainment (eg music, dancing or indoor sporting events)</li>\n  <li>serving hot food or drink between 11pm and 5am\t</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You will also need a <abbr title=\"Temporary Event Notice\">TEN</abbr> if a particular licensable activity is not included in the terms of your existing licence, eg holding a wedding reception at a community centre.</p>\n\n<h2>Restrictions</h2>\n\n<p>Your event must:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>have less than 500 people at any one time &ndash; including staff running the event</li>\n  <li>last no more than 168 hours, or 7 days</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You must be at least 18 to apply for a Temporary Event Notice.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Number of notices you can apply for</h3>\n\n<p>You will need a <abbr title=\"Temporary Event Notice\">TEN</abbr> for each event you hold on the same premises.</p>\n\n<p>You can get up to 5 <abbr title=\"Temporary Event Notices\">TENs</abbr> a year. If you already have a personal licence to sell alcohol, you can be given up to 50 <abbr title=\"Temporary Event Notices\">TENs</abbr> a year. </p>\n\n<p>A single premises can have up to 12 notices applied for in 1 year, as long as:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>the total length of the events is not more than 21 days</li>\n  <li>1 person doesn&rsquo;t make more than 5 applications for the premises</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>&lsquo;Late <abbr title=\"Temporary Event Notices\">TENs</abbr>&rsquo;</h3>\n\n<p>You can apply for a &lsquo;late <abbr title=\"Temporary Event Notice\">TEN</abbr>&rsquo; up to 5 working days before the event. You can apply for up to 10 late <abbr title=\"Temporary Event Notices\">TENs</abbr> per calendar year. </p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>If you are organising separate but consecutive events, there must be at least a 24 hour gap between them.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>If you don&rsquo;t hold a personal licence, you can serve up to 5 notices (of which up to 2 may be late).  </p>\n\n<p>If you hold a personal licence, the limit is 50 notices (of which up to 10 may be late).</p>\n\n<h2>How to apply</h2>\n\n<p>Contact <a href=\"/find-your-local-council\" title=\"Find your local council\">your council</a> to apply for a <abbr title=\"Temporary Event Notice\">TEN</abbr>. You must do this at least 10 working days before your event. </p>\n\n<p>You will have to pay a fee of £21.</p>\n\n<p>You must send a copy of the <abbr title=\"Temporary Event Notice\">TEN</abbr> to the police at least 10 working days before the event &ndash; if you apply online, the council will contact the police for you. </p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>The date of submitting the <abbr title=\"Temporary Event Notice\">TEN</abbr> and the day of the event are not included in the total number of working days before the event.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Objections</h2>\n<p>The council can&rsquo;t refuse a notice unless the police or Environmental Health object to it. They must do this within 3 working days of receiving it. They can only object if they think your event could:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>lead to crime and disorder</li>\n  <li>cause a public nuisance</li>\n  <li>be a threat to public safety</li>\n  <li>put children at risk of harm</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If there&rsquo;s an objection, your council&rsquo;s licensing committee will hold a meeting &ndash; called a &lsquo;hearing&rsquo; &ndash; no later than 24 hours before the event.</p>\n\n<p>At the hearing, the committee will either approve, add conditions or reject the notice.</p>\n\n<h2>Appeals</h2>\n<p>If you disagree with the licensing committee&rsquo;s decision, you can appeal to your local Magistrates&rsquo; court. You must do this within 21 days, and at least 5 working days before the date of your event.</p>\n\n<h2>Displaying your notice</h2>\n\n<p>You must keep your <abbr title=\"Temporary Event Notice\">TEN</abbr> in a safe place where the event is held. </p>\n\n<p>You must also display a copy of the notice where it can be easily seen.</p>\n\n<h2>Fines and penalties</h2>\n\n<p>You can only apply for a <abbr title=\"Temporary Event Notice\">TEN</abbr> as an individual, not an organisation.</p>\n\n<p>You could be fined up to £5,000 if you make any false statements in your application, or face prosecution if you breach the terms of the notice.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>If you don’t have a <abbr title=\"Temporary Event Notice\">TEN</abbr> and carry out an activity that you should have a licence for (or allow your premises to be used for one), you can be fined £20,000, sent to prison for up to 6 months, or both.</p>\n</div>\n\n"},"tags":[{"title":"Business Link","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/businesslink.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":null,"short_description":null,"type":"legacy_source"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=businesslink","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/businesslink"},"parent":null},{"title":"Licences and licence applications","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/business%2Flicences.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Applying for licences from your council for events and businesses","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=business%2Flicences","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/business/licences"},"parent":{"title":"Businesses and self-employed","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/business.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Information about starting up and running a business in the UK, including help if you're self employed or a sole trader.","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=business","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/business"},"parent":null}}],"related":[{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/contact-police.json","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/contact-police","title":"Contact the police","format":"answer","updated_at":"2012-10-22T15:20:38+00:00"},{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/apply-hold-street-party.json","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/apply-hold-street-party","title":"Apply to hold a street party","format":"local_transaction","updated_at":"2012-10-22T15:17:03+00:00"}]}]}